from pathlib import Path
import base64, zlib, re

JOINT = ''''''

pages = [
 'nocatee-driveway-paver-sealing.html','nocatee-pool-deck-paver-sealing.html',
 'nocatee-travertine-sealing.html','nocatee-house-washing.html','nocatee-roof-washing.html',
 'paver-sealing-cost-calculator.html','privacy-policy.html','warranty.html'
]
for name in pages:
    p=Path(name); s=p.read_text(encoding='utf-8')
    s=s.replace('class="breadcrumbs"','class="breadcrumb"')
    p.write_text(s,encoding='utf-8')

# Replace the short joint-sand page with the detailed user-supplied version.
joint=zlib.decompress(base64.b64decode(JOINT)).decode('utf-8')
joint=re.sub(r'\n\s*<style>.*?</style>','',joint,count=1,flags=re.S|re.I)
joint=joint.replace('<a href="/paver-sealing-cost-calculator">Cost Calculator</a>\n      </nav>', '<a href="/paver-sealing-cost-calculator">Cost Calculator</a> &middot;\n        <a href="/warranty">Warranty</a> &middot;\n        <a href="/privacy-policy">Privacy</a>\n      </nav>')
Path('nocatee-paver-joint-sand.html').write_text(joint,encoding='utf-8')

# Add substantive driveway depth without repeating pricing or FAQs.
p=Path('nocatee-driveway-paver-sealing.html'); s=p.read_text(encoding='utf-8')
if 'When driveway sealing should wait' not in s:
    block='''\n      <section class="section split">\n        <div><p class="eyebrow">Project readiness</p><h2>When driveway sealing should wait</h2><p>A driveway should not be sealed simply because the calendar says it is time. Active drainage problems, standing water, unstable or rocking pavers, severe settlement, fresh repairs, saturated joints and a failed incompatible coating can all change the correct sequence. Sealer can improve appearance and help stabilize properly prepared joints, but it cannot rebuild a failed base or stop water from moving through a problem area.</p><p>HydroSeal checks low points, edge restraint, joint depth, previous coating condition and weather exposure before scheduling application. If repairs, stripping or additional drying are needed, those steps should be completed first rather than covered by a new finish.</p></div>\n        <div><p class="eyebrow">Complete restoration</p><h2>What should be included beyond pressure washing</h2><p>A complete Nocatee driveway paver restoration includes more than removing surface dirt. The work should account for rust and irrigation staining, organic buildup, oil or tire marks, loose joint material, sunken units, failed sealer and the moisture condition of the driveway before application.</p><p>Cleaning pressure and chemistry should match the paver and coating. Joint sand should be restored after cleaning and agreed repairs. The surface should then be allowed to dry and checked before breathable sealer is applied at the appropriate rate. Homeowners should receive clear cure-time, irrigation and vehicle instructions at completion.</p></div>\n      </section>\n'''
    s=s.replace('      <section class="section gallery-embed" aria-label="Recent reviews">',block+'      <section class="section gallery-embed" aria-label="Recent reviews">',1)
p.write_text(s,encoding='utf-8')

# Add pool-deck-specific depth.
p=Path('nocatee-pool-deck-paver-sealing.html'); s=p.read_text(encoding='utf-8')
if 'Pool-deck sealing should account for water, shade and traction' not in s:
    block='''\n      <section class="section split">\n        <div><p class="eyebrow">Wet-area planning</p><h2>Pool-deck sealing should account for water, shade and traction</h2><p>A screened Nocatee pool deck behaves differently from an open driveway. Shade and reduced airflow can extend drying time, while splash-out, rain entering the enclosure, irrigation near the screen line and routine pool maintenance repeatedly wet the surface. Product selection and application rate must account for the material, existing coating, texture and how the deck drains.</p><p>Any wet paver or stone can become slippery. Sealer does not create one universal traction result: texture, finish, contaminants, maintenance and standing water all matter. HydroSeal reviews these factors before recommending a finish and explains that regular cleaning remains necessary after sealing.</p></div>\n        <div><p class="eyebrow">Preparation</p><h2>Coping, drains and screened edges need separate attention</h2><p>Pool decks often collect organic buildup at screen edges, beneath furniture and around planters. Joint loss can be strongest near drains and areas where water repeatedly crosses the deck. Coping, natural stone and concrete pavers may also require different cleaning methods even when they are part of the same project.</p><p>Before sealing, agreed repairs should be completed, joints restored, residue removed and moisture conditions verified. Pool equipment, waterline areas, screen components and adjacent landscaping should be considered in the work plan. Sealing cannot correct a failed base, poor drainage or loose coping, so those conditions should be identified rather than hidden.</p></div>\n      </section>\n'''
    marker='      <section class="section gallery-embed" aria-label="Recent reviews">'
    if marker in s: s=s.replace(marker,block+marker,1)
    else: s=s.replace('    </main>',block+'    </main>',1)
p.write_text(s,encoding='utf-8')

# Expand the policy pages with complete visible terms.
privacy=Path('privacy-policy.html'); s=privacy.read_text(encoding='utf-8')
main='''<main><section class="section"><p class="eyebrow">Last updated July 23, 2026</p><h1>Privacy Policy</h1><p>This policy explains how HydroSeal and the Nocatee Paver Sealing website collect, use, retain and share information when you request an estimate, send project photos, call, text, email or use embedded website tools.</p><h2>Information you provide</h2><p>You may provide your name, telephone number, email address, service address, neighborhood, project measurements, preferred contact method, scheduling details, messages and photos or videos of the property. Do not send sensitive financial, medical or identity information through a quote form or chatbot.</p><h2>Information collected automatically</h2><p>Hosting, security, analytics and embedded-service providers may receive basic device, browser, IP address, page-view, referral and interaction information. Cookies or similar technologies may be used to operate forms, remember settings, measure performance, prevent abuse and understand how visitors use the site.</p><h2>How information is used</h2><ul><li>Review and price requested work.</li><li>Contact you about estimates, scheduling, service and follow-up.</li><li>Maintain project, warranty, accounting and customer-service records.</li><li>Operate, secure and improve the website.</li><li>Comply with legal, insurance, tax and safety requirements.</li></ul><h2>Text messages and calls</h2><p>When you provide a phone number or initiate a call or text, HydroSeal may respond about your inquiry or project. Message and data rates may apply. You can ask not to receive nonessential follow-up messages, but transactional communication may still be needed for active estimates or scheduled work.</p><h2>Project photographs</h2><p>Photos you submit are used to evaluate the project. HydroSeal will not intentionally publish customer-submitted photos that clearly identify a person, address, vehicle plate or private information without permission. Completed-project images may be used for records, warranty review or marketing when permitted.</p><h2>Third-party services</h2><p>The site may use hosting, quote-form, analytics, review, gallery, chatbot, communications or map providers. Information processed through those tools may be governed by the provider's terms and privacy practices. HydroSeal does not control every third-party service or website linked from this site.</p><h2>Sharing and sale of information</h2><p>HydroSeal does not sell personal information. Information may be shared with service providers that support website hosting, communications, scheduling, payments, accounting, insurance or legal compliance, and when reasonably necessary to protect customers, the business or others.</p><h2>Retention</h2><p>Quote and project information may be retained for customer service, warranty, tax, insurance, dispute and recordkeeping purposes. Information that is no longer reasonably needed may be deleted or de-identified, subject to backup and legal-retention limitations.</p><h2>Security</h2><p>Reasonable administrative and technical safeguards are used, but no website, email, text message or online storage system can guarantee absolute security. Use ordinary caution when sending property details or images.</p><h2>Your choices</h2><p>You may request access, correction or deletion of information HydroSeal controls. Some records may be retained when required for contracts, warranty administration, accounting, insurance, safety or legal obligations.</p><h2>Contact</h2><p>Questions or requests may be sent to <a href="mailto:info@hydrosealpavers.com">info@hydrosealpavers.com</a> or <a href="tel:+19045375000">904-537-5000</a>.</p></section></main>'''
s=re.sub(r'<main>.*?</main>',main,s,count=1,flags=re.S)
privacy.write_text(s,encoding='utf-8')

warranty=Path('warranty.html'); s=warranty.read_text(encoding='utf-8')
main='''<main><section class="section"><p class="eyebrow">Written project coverage</p><h1>HydroSeal Paver Sealing Warranty</h1><p>Qualifying paver sealing projects include a written two-year workmanship and adhesion warranty. This page explains the general program. The signed proposal, invoice and project-specific warranty control if their terms differ from this summary.</p><h2>Eligibility</h2><p>Coverage applies only when the proposal or invoice states that the project qualifies, the account is paid in full, HydroSeal performed the covered preparation and sealer application, and the homeowner follows the written cure and maintenance instructions. Repairs, stripping, stain treatment, walls, coping, natural stone or other specialty work are covered only when specifically included in writing.</p><h2>When coverage begins</h2><p>The warranty period begins on the date the covered sealing work is completed, unless the written project documents state another date. A return visit for furniture, inspection or unrelated work does not restart or extend the warranty period.</p><h2>What is covered</h2><p>The warranty addresses covered workmanship and sealer-adhesion failures caused by HydroSeal's application on the agreed work area. After inspection, the remedy may include localized preparation and reapplication or another reasonable corrective step selected for the condition. The warranty is a repair warranty and does not guarantee a cash refund, full replacement or a permanently unchanged appearance.</p><h2>Appearance changes that are not automatically defects</h2><p>Gloss reduction, normal wear, traffic patterns, color variation, natural-stone variation, tire marks, dirt, organic buildup and gradual weathering do not by themselves establish an adhesion or workmanship failure. Wet surfaces can appear darker, and shade, moisture and underlying paver color can create variation across the same project.</p><h2>Exclusions</h2><ul><li>Efflorescence, mineral migration, reclaimed-water deposits, rust and irrigation staining.</li><li>Standing water, drainage defects, moisture vapor, hydrostatic pressure or water entering from below or adjacent areas.</li><li>Paver movement, settlement, rocking units, failed base, erosion, edge-restraint failure or damage caused by roots.</li><li>Weeds, ants, insects, joint-sand loss caused by water flow, pressure washing, excavation or pest activity.</li><li>Oil, fertilizer, chemicals, pool chemicals, salt, paint, tire compounds or other stains and contaminants.</li><li>Storms, flooding, wind-driven debris, construction, vehicle damage, abuse, neglect or work performed by others.</li><li>Damage from pressure washing, harsh cleaners, incompatible coatings or maintenance products applied after service.</li><li>Pre-existing coating failure, hidden moisture, repairs or defects that were not part of the agreed scope.</li></ul><h2>Required care and maintenance</h2><p>Keep foot traffic, vehicles, sprinklers, rain runoff and furniture off the surface for the project-specific cure period. Prevent irrigation overspray where practical. Clean spills promptly with compatible methods, avoid aggressive pressure close to joints, and do not apply another coating or chemical treatment without checking compatibility. Routine cleaning, weed control, ant control and future joint maintenance remain the owner's responsibility.</p><h2>Warranty claim process</h2><ol class="steps"><li><strong>Contact HydroSeal promptly:</strong> provide the service address, completion date and a description of the concern.</li><li><strong>Send clear photos:</strong> include wide views and close-ups taken when the surface is dry.</li><li><strong>Preserve the condition:</strong> do not pressure wash, coat, repair or allow another contractor to alter the area before review.</li><li><strong>Allow inspection:</strong> HydroSeal must receive reasonable access and time to inspect weather, drainage, moisture, contamination and the affected surface.</li><li><strong>Corrective work:</strong> if the condition is covered, HydroSeal will schedule a reasonable remedy based on weather, cure requirements and access.</li></ol><h2>Limits</h2><p>No coating can prevent all fading, staining, moisture effects, surface wear, weeds, ants or movement. The warranty is limited to the covered work and remedy described in the project documents. It does not extend manufacturer warranties or cover consequential costs such as loss of use, landscaping, pool service, vehicle storage or work performed by others.</p><h2>Request a warranty review</h2><p>Email <a href="mailto:info@hydrosealpavers.com">info@hydrosealpavers.com</a> or call <a href="tel:+19045375000">904-537-5000</a>. Include the property address, project date, photos and a brief timeline of when the issue appeared.</p></section></main>'''
s=re.sub(r'<main>.*?</main>',main,s,count=1,flags=re.S)
warranty.write_text(s,encoding='utf-8')
